                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>
                        <collation>In the present condition, the structure
                           of the remaining quires looks as follows:
                           <list>
                              <item xml:id="q1">
                                 <dim unit="leaf">2</dim>
                                 <locus from="1r" to="2v"/> I (2/fols. 1r-2v) </item>
                              <item xml:id="q2">
                                 <dim unit="leaf">5</dim>
                                 <locus from="3r" to="7v"/> II (5; s.l. 2, stub after 4/fols. 3r-7v) </item>
                              <item xml:id="q3">
                                 <dim unit="leaf">4</dim>
                                 <locus from="8r" to="11v"/> III (4/fols. 8r-11v) </item>
                              <item xml:id="q4">
                                 <dim unit="leaf">2</dim>
                                 <locus from="12r" to="13v"/> IV (2/fols. 12r-13v) </item>
                              <item xml:id="q5">
                                 <dim unit="leaf">8</dim>
                                 <locus from="14r" to="21v"/> V (8; s.l.: 3, stub after 5; 6, stub
                                 after 2/fols. 14r-21v) </item>
                              <item xml:id="q6">
                                 <dim unit="leaf">4</dim>
                                 <locus from="22r" to="25v"/> VI (4/fols. 22r-25v).</item>
                           </list>
                        </collation>
                        
                        <condition key="deficient">Both boards, the original sewing and many leaves
                           are missing. The remaining leaves are roughly bound by a cord; most of
                           the leaves are damaged by humidity and water (e.g.: <locus target="#8r">8r</locus>, 12v, 13r, 14r). The preserved text is mostly readable.
                           There are a few holes (esp. in <locus target="#8v">8v</locus>, 17v, 18r);
                           some leaves are apparently damaged by rodents (esp. <locus target="#1rv">1rv</locus>, 2rv). A loose bifolium has been catalogued as <ref type="mss" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/ESam047">AM-047</ref></condition>
                     </supportDesc>
